          <Comment>This sequence change creates a premature translational stop signal (p.Ser842Hisfs*10) in the CLCN1 gene. While this is not anticipated to result in nonsense mediated decay, it is expected to disrupt the last 147 amino acid(s) of the CLCN1 protein. This variant is not present in population databases (gnomAD no frequency). This variant has not been reported in the literature in individuals affected with CLCN1-related conditions. This variant disrupts a region of the CLCN1 protein in which other variant(s) (p.Gly945Argfs*39) have been determined to be pathogenic (PMID: 18337100; Invitae). This suggests that this is a clinically significant region of the protein, and that variants that disrupt it are likely to be disease-causing. For these reasons, this variant has been classified as Pathogenic.</Comment>
